{"title": "Complete Works of Brann, the Iconoclast, Volume 1", "description": "William Cowper Brann earned the nickname \u201cThe Iconoclast\u201d by fearlessly attacking established beliefs and institutions which he thought to be pompous and self-serving. He settled in the wild and wooly West Texas town of Waco in the late 1800s as a newspaper man - first as a writer and then as owner of newspaper he named \u201cThe Iconoclast\u201d. During this period, Catholics and Protestants were duking it out over the soul of Texas and there was even further sectarian strife among Protestants. Brann wrote prolifically and aired his Politically Incorrect views with vigor and colorful language.\n\nDescribed as a \u201cslouch-hatted, gun-toting, beer-drinking, woman-worshiping man,\u201d he assailed Baptists, Prohibition, blacks and universities as though engaged in a life-or-death gunfight; and actually he was killed in a gunfight at age 43. After he was shot in the back, drew his own gun and killed the man who had bushwacked him AND THEN walked directly to the jail before dying the next morning.\nHe wrote entertaining, elevated prose; but occasionally colored his stories with barnyard terminology. Despite his blatant chauvinism, his voice was a reaction against many of the societal extremes of the day. ( William Jones ) ", "duration": 45451, "language": "English", "authors": [{"id": "14034", "name": "William Cowper Brann"}], "coverArt": "https://archive.org/download/brann_volume_1_1906_librivox/iconoclast1_1906.jpg", "copyright_year": "1896", "genres": ["Essays & Short Works", "Modern (19th C)"], "supporters": [{"role": "Read by", "name": "LibriVox Volunteers"}, {"role": "Book Coordinator", "name": "William Allan Jones"}, {"role": "Meta Coordinator", "name": "Lynne T"}, {"role": "Proof Listener", "name": "Michele Fry"}], "sections": [{"section": 0, "title": "Introduction and Preface", "readers": [10996], "path": "https://www.archive.org/download/brann_volume_1_1906_librivox/ico